AGI -&nbsp;&nbsp;The two Russian planes, of the model IL 20, intercepted in two separate episodes from the Italian hunt on the Baltic Sea, were flying over an international airspace on the border with NATO. It's learned from Defense sources. The alert system that led to the 'scramble' is triggered by lack of contact by aircraft with air traffic management control towers.
&nbsp;
For twice in 24 hours i&nbsp;Caccia&nbsp;italiani in service in the Polish base of Malbork had intercepted two Russian spy aircraft which, according to the sources, did not have 'hostile intentions'. The NATO Air Operations Control and Control Centre (CAOC) based in Uedem (Germany) launched the alarm to intercept in the mornings of 28 and today, March 29, an unidentified aircraft. The planes of the Italian Air Force belonging to the TFA - operating within the NATO mission of Enhanced Air Policing - had proceeded to intercept and identify the aircraft, and then return to the base of Malbork.
<h2> Italian drivers stationed in Poland</h2>
The Task Force Air "4th Wing" based in Malbork employs four Eurofighter (F-2000) aircraft from four Air Force Air Defence Stories: 4 Storm of Grosseto, 36 Storm of Gioia del Colle, 37 Storm of Trapani and 51 Storm of Istrana. Thanks to these aircraft it is possible to ensure the take-off and interception of any suspected track detected by radar in a few minutes, 24 hours on 24, 365 days a year.
&nbsp;
The Italian contingent, under the direct national dependence of the Covi (Operative Command of Interforze Summit), is composed of women and men of the Air Force coming from the Groups of Flight and technical and logistic staff, deployed at the Krolewo airport of Malbork, who operate alongside the Polish Air Force to protect the north-east flank of the Atlantic Alliance. This is the second time an Italian contingent is employed in Poland in enhanced Air Policing.&nbsp operations;
